{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Height and Width","slug":"css-height-width","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Beginner","estimated_read_time":"10 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Box Model"],"learning_objectives":["Set height and width of elements","Understand max-width and min-width","Understand max-height and min-height","Content overflow handling"],"theory":"The `height` and `width` properties are used to set the height and width of an element. \n\nThey can take values in:\n*   **Pixels (`px`)**: Fixed size.\n*   **Percentage (`%`)**: Relative to the parent element.\n*   **`auto`**: Default. The browser calculates the size.\n\n`max-width` is crucial for responsive design: it allows an element to shrink if the screen is small, but stops it from growing beyond a certain point.","syntax":"div {\n  height: 200px;\n  width: 50%;\n  max-width: 500px;\n}","examples":[{"code":"div.container {\n  width: 100%;\n  max-width: 800px;\n  margin: auto;\n}","output":"A container that spans full width on mobiles but stops at 800px on desktops, centered.","explanation":"This is a standard pattern for readable content blocks."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using width: 100% with padding/margin","correction":"This often causes horizontal scrollbars. Use `max-width: 100%` or `box-sizing: border-box`.","example":""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What happens if content is larger than the set height?","answer":"Currently, it will overflow (spill out) of the box unless `overflow` property is set.","difficulty":"Medium"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Create a box that is at least 300px wide but can grow larger.","hint":"Use min-width.","solution":"min-width: 300px;","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Responsive Images","description":"Images should scale down but never scale up beyond their original quality.","code":"img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; }"}],"exam_notes":["Default width of block elements is 'auto' (takes full ava